"Nobre C.A., Borma L.D.S.","'Tipping points' for the Amazon forest",2009,"Current Opinion in Environmental Sustainability","1","1",,"28","36",,,10.1016/j.cosust.2009.07.003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70449389061&partnerID=40&md5=67b12aefccaedbef17c1aa8611552100","Center for Earth System Science, National Institute for Space Research - INPE, São José dos Campos, SP, Brazil","Nobre, C.A., Center for Earth System Science, National Institute for Space Research - INPE, São José dos Campos, SP, Brazil; Borma, L.D.S., Center for Earth System Science, National Institute for Space Research - INPE, São José dos Campos, SP, Brazil","The stability of the Amazon forest-climate equilibrium is being perturbed by a number of human drivers of change (e.g. deforestation, global warming, forest fires, higher CO2 concentrations, and increased frequency of droughts and floods). Quantitative assessments for the maintenance of the tropical forest indicate that 'tipping points' may exist for total deforested area (&gt;40%) and for global warming (ΔT &gt; 3-4°C). The likelihood of exceeding a tipping point can be greatly exacerbated by increases in forest fires and droughts, but quantification of those effects is still lacking. Forest resilience can be significantly increased if CO2 'fertilization' effect is proven to be taking place for tropical forests, but it can be offset by continued increases in temperature, rainfall seasonality, and forest fires. © 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.",,"carbon dioxide; deforestation; drought; forest fire; global warming; human activity; nature-society relations; quantitative analysis; seasonality; tropical forest; Amazonia; South America",,,,,,"Dirzo, R., Raven, P.H., Global state of biodiversity and loss (2003) Annu Rev Env Res, 28, pp. 137-167; Field, C.B., Behrenfeld, M.J., Randerson, J.T., Falkowski, P., Primary production of the biosphere: integrating terrestrial and oceanic components (1998) Science, 281, pp. 237-240; Nobre, C.A., Sellers, P.J., Shukla, J., Amazonian deforestation and regional climate change (1991) J Climate, 4, pp. 957-988; Betts, R.A., Malhi, Y., Roberts, J.T., The future of the Amazon: new perspectives from climate, ecosystem and social sciences (2008) Philos Trans R Soc B, 363, pp. 1729-1735. , The paper introduces a multidisciplinary analysis of the challenges of the Amazon forest in the view of the ongoing degradation of forest and respective threats to the local and global climate stability; Malhi, Y.R., Wood, D., Baker, T., Wright, J.S., Phillips, O.L., Cochrane, T., Meir, P., Arroyo, L., The regional variation of aboveground live biomass in old-growth Amazonian forests (2006) Global Change Biol, 12, pp. 1107-1138. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2486.2006.01120.x; Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Especiais, (2008) Monitoring of the Brazilian Amazonian Forest by Satellite. PRODES, DETER, DEGRAD and QUEIMADAS Systems, 2007-2008, , http://www.obt.inpe.br/prodes/Relatorio_Prodes2008.pdf, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Especiais, São José dos Campos, Brazil available in http://www.obt.inpe.br/prodes/Relatorio_Prodes2008.pdf; Lenton, T.M., Held, H., Kriegler, E., Hall, J.W., Lucht, W., Rahmstorf, S., Schellnhuber, H.J., Tipping elements in the Earth's climate system (2008) Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 105, pp. 1786-1793. , doi_10.1073_pnas.0705414105; Oyama, M.D., Nobre, C.A., A new climate-vegetation equilibrium state for tropical South America (2003) Geophys Res Lett, 30 (23), p. 2199. , doi:10.1029/2003GL018600; Foley, J.A., Asner, G.P., Costa, M.H., Coe, M.T., DeFries, R., Gibbs, H.K., Howard, E.A., Snyder, P., Amazonia revealed: forest degradation and loss of ecosystem goods and services in the Amazon Basin (2007) Front Ecol Environ, 5, pp. 25-32; Sampaio, G., Nobre, C., Costa, M.H., Satyamurty, P., Soares-Filho, B.S., Cardoso, M., Regional climate change over eastern Amazonia caused by pasture and soybean cropland expansion (2007) Geophys Res Lett, 34, pp. L17709. , Using simulated land cover maps from a business-as-usual scenario of future deforestation in which rainforest was gradually replaced by degraded pasture or by soybean cropland, the authors found an accelerating decrease in rainfall for increasing deforestation (>40% of the original forest cover) for both classes of land use conversions; Salazar, L.F., Nobre, C.A., Oyama, M.D., Climate change consequences on the biome distribution in tropical South America (2007) Geophys Res Lett, 34, pp. L09708. , The consequences of projected climate change on biome distribution in South America are analyzed through a potential vegetation model forced with the IPCC climate change scenarios. The results indicate the reduction of tropical forest cover and replacement by savannas mostly over southeastern Amazonia reaching a reduction of 18% for the 2090-2099 period (A2 emission scenario); Malhi, Y., Roberts, J.T.R., Betts, R.A., Killeen, T.J., Li, W., Nobre, C.A., Climate change, deforestation, and the fate of the Amazon (2008) Science, 319, pp. 169-172.. , doi:10.1126/science.1146961. The authors presented a review about the fate of Amazon forest summarizing some of the latest findings about the threats (deforestation, climate changes and fire, consequences and conservation strategies for the forest ecosystem; Lapola, D.M., Oyama, M.D., Nobre, C.A., Exploring the range of climate-biome projections for tropical South America: the role of CO2 fertilization and seasonality (2009) Global Biogeochem Cycles, 23, pp. GB3003. , doi:10.1029/2008GB003357; Barlow, J., Peres, C.A., Fire-mediated dieback and compositional cascade in an Amazonian forest (2008) Philos Trans R Soc B, 363, pp. 1787-1794. , doi:10.1098/rstb.2007.0013. Through experimental plots the authors analyzed the long-term consequences of forest fires in Brazilian Amazon. The results show that the fires drastically alter forest structure and composition, leading to a rapid impoverishment of forests over a relatively short period of time; Nepstad, D.C., Stickler, C.M., Filho, B.S., Merry, F., Interactions among Amazon land use, forests and climate: prospects for a near-term forest tipping point (2008) Philos Trans R Soc B, 363, pp. 1737-1746. , doi:10.1098/rstb.2007.0036. The authors presented a review of interaction between human drivers of change and forest and depict some quantitative values for the fate of Amazon forest: if sea surface temperatures anomalies and associated Amazon droughts continue into the future, approximately 55% of the Amazon forests will be cleared, logged and damaged over the 20 years, emitting 15-26 Pg of carbon to the atmosphere; Marengo, J.A., Nobre, C.A., Tomasella, J., Cardoso, M.F., Oyama, M.D., Hydro-climatic and ecological behaviour of the drought of Amazonia in 2005 (2008) Philos Trans R Soc B, 363, pp. 1773-1778. , doi:10.1098/rstb.2007.0015; INPE/CPTEC Climanalise. nr. 1, , http://climanalise.cptec.inpe.br/∼rclimanl/boletim/index0106.shtml, Jan 2006; INPE/CPTEC Infoclima. Boletim de Informações Climáticas. nr. 5, 2009, 3 p. http://infoclima1.cptec.inpe.br/Phillips, O.L., Aragão, L.E.O.C., Lewis, S.L., Fisher, J.B., Lloyd, J., López-González, G., Malhi, Y., Quesada, C.A., Drought sensitivity of the Amazon rainforest (2009) Science, 323, pp. 1344-1347; Soares-Filho, B.S., Nepstad, D.C., Curran, L.M., Cerqueira, G.C., Garcia, R.A., Ramos, C.A., Voll, E., Schlesinger, P., Modelling conservation in the Amazon basin (2006) Nature, 440, pp. 520-523; Hansen, M.C., Shimabukuro, Y.E., Potapov, P., Pittman, K., Comparing annual MODIS and PRODES forest cover change data for advancing monitoring of Brazilian forest cover (2008) Remote Sens Environ, 112, pp. 3784-3793; Hansen, M.C., Stehman, S.V., Potapov, P.V., Loveland, T.R., Townshends, J.R.G., DeFries, R.S., Pittman, K.W., Steininger, M.K., Humid tropical forest clearing from 2000 to 2005 quantified by using multitemporal and multiresolution remotely sensed data (2008) Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A, 27, pp. 9439-9444